text: Magkita tayo - Let's see each other (imperative form, as an invitation/suggestion). Sana (ay) magkita tayo - I hope we see each other (in English the verb stays in simple present, in Tagalog it stays in the imperative, but note: the imperative is not always formed with the same prefix "mag", some look identical to the past form conjugation, and not all "mag" words are in the imperative--other Filipino languages are more consistent and this will mess non-Tagalog Filipinos up so you might hear similar mistakes around you). Magkikita tayo - we will see each other (future tense, in English this also does not go well with "hope", "wish") this is purely a prediction, a statement of a future (scheduled) action/event, or a promise, i.e. Pangako ko sa'yo, magkikita tayong muli.

text: The thing with live streams is that you need to have a strong and consistent network connection that has a high rate of transfer. So this helps eliminate any lagging and pixelation of images/audio. Also, depending on where you are, one network connection from one provider would be stronger than the connection you maybe using. You can use a personal hotspot that you can connect to while you do your live streams as long as you know your hotspot connection provider delivers consistent high speed connectivity. In that way you're assured that your live stream videos can deliver the best viewing experience. Also, in this way you're no relying entirely on your phone's cellular connection.
author: @WanderlustDayWalks

text: I don't suggest having merchandise if you are contemplating the product to offer because it is prone to be abused if you don't have control over it. Others might use your name or trademark and copy your product for their benefit. But you can test the water by offering limited-edition and limited numbers of merchandise for every milestone of your life, maybe a souvenir of you for us to keep.

text: Collaborations and TV guesting are great ways to grow your channel. It is also an opportunity to reach other types of viewers. If there is a chance, it's best to grab opportunities that will benefit you to better prepare for your future or if you plan to have a family. We don't know what will happen in the future if you are still the same man who is physically fit and able to communicate well and do vlogging. It's not wrong to dream big and secure your future. You can collaborate with people with the same interests as yours. You can choose projects or TV guesting to help you achieve your goals that will not compromise your values and reputation. But still, it's up to you to decide what you think is best for you and will make you happy. Always pray for His wisdom and knowledge. Always acknowledge God in everything you do and thank Him for all the blessings and favors He has given you. Not all people were lucky enough to receive offers as you.

text: Yung refrigerator dapat nasa kusina. Siguro, you can put it right next to your stove. You can put a table (or a cabinet) in between the stove and fridge, and the gas tank underneath the table. Tapos, yung cabinet (kung nasaan yung fridge right now) is an entertainment center. You can put a plant or a cabinet in there). Actually, dining area yung kung nasaan ang TV ninyo right now, kaya may tatlong ilaw sa ceiling. You can put the dining table right next to the wall (pahaba), put two chairs on each end, and the bench in the middle, kaya tamang-tama para sa family. Maybe, you can move the TV higher. Tapos, yung L-shape sofa ninyo, i-deretso nalang ninyo against the wall para mas spacious ang living/dining area and the walkway to your masters bedroom and kitchen. Suggestion lang ito ha. text: I lived near Manila for three years and observed some behaviors that left me frustrated. For example, I often saw people littering, urinating in public, and neglecting basic hygiene in their daily lives, such as unclean hands or kitchens. These experiences made me question whether these issues stem from a lack of education or other societal challenges.I also noticed some cultural habits that surprised me, such as women engaging in behaviors like spitting or not prioritizing personal grooming. Instead of addressing these, some seemed to simply cover up with makeup. Sadly, these impressions have left me unable to recommend the Philippines as a holiday destination.I found that preparing even simple meals or handling basic tasks like counting without a calculator seemed uncommon for some, and the increasing amount of garbage in the environment is concerning. Additionally, the frequent calls of "Hi Joe!" and interactions focused on money made me feel unwelcome at times, as though sincerity was lacking.I advise travelers to the Philippines to exercise caution and be mindful of potential scams. While there are certainly kind and genuine individuals, my overall experience was mixed, leaving me with some reservations about the country.

text: For the non-locals in the comment section, "Marites" is a play on the phrase, "Mare, anong latest?" which translates to "Sis - or any close confidant - what's the latest?" meaning rumors/gossips. So being a "Marites"" is a term for a gossipy character, stereotypically a female. "Mare" came from the word "kumare" which literally means she's a 'godmother' to one of your children but now, infornally, refers to any female friends or relatives. The male counterpart is called "Kumpare" shortened to "pare" which is now used to address/refer to any male within your age group, give or take a few, e.g. "Pare, how have you been?" Although tnere is no "Parites" term to reference the male specie, there should be. Incidentally, Marites is a popular female name in the Philippines that means "lady of the sea" and a combination of the Spanish names "Maria" and "Teresa".

text: hehe as a Chilean I'm surprised with the use of "po" in Tagalog. well, many people can argue that we don't speak Spanish but we officially do, hehe. text: "tao po?" is like a common expression. It has "po" in it because you are still showing respect to a person who owns the home or establishment. "May tao po ba?" is used in a more formal setting because it is showing more respect. Think if it as a more polite way of saying it. And the word ingat is pronounced (ee ngat) the "ng" would be said with the same ng sound you would find in words such as "tongue" and "lung". It sounds like you're saying nat, but you have a slight ng sound to it.

text: Some senators identified themselves as "LAWMAKERS" but they violated the Law and disrespects the Very Constitution. They took an "OATH" to uphold the constitution and swore to remain "IMPARTIAL" on the Impeachment trial. But before the trial could have started, majority of them had showed being "biased" already. 1. Some of them are lawyering the VP, when in fact they are supposed to be there AS "PROSECUTORS" to hear the impeachment process and not to hinder or obstruct. 2. Calling it "Dismissed" is not in the constitutional mandate.3. They are supposed to be "LAWMAKERS" of the people and not an acting "LAWYER" of the VP. But they are paid by the people's taxes and elected by the people.4. They took the"OATH" BUT "NEVER" took the oath earnestly by heart. Those Senators are Abusing thier Constitutional mandate, and disrespects the people as well as to the Constitution. Very absurd and traitor move against the people. It only shows that they are not sincere in thier position as a "LAWMAKERS" even to the extend of taking the oath in an open. So What can people expect behind close doors.IMEE Marcos is going beyond her consitutional mandate. From Defending the VP AGAINST ALLEGED MISUSED OF FUNDS, TO MEETING FPRRD LEGAL COUNSEL, NOW ASKING FOR AN INTERIM RELEASE. THAT IS TOO MUCH. She had forgotten the welfare of the people, she had disregarded the victims of crimes committed by FPRRD. These Senators are not just disrespectful of thier duty to serve, the tax payers but also those who contributed the 1987 Constitution.It felt like, there is no longer a Government because majority are defying the constitution but making thier own policy on how the government works. Everyone is abusing thier power as much as they can without holding accountability because no one sanctions them. They do not care our country to remain a third world county because of corruption, because those powerless and regular people are the major taxpayers. This is a modern day slavery. No fair justice and impartiality.

text: As a Filipino, it‚Äôs funny and silly to realize that most foreigners in the comment section took her question seriously and misunderstood what‚Äôs happening in this video. It just goes to show how naive some people can be about Filipino culture lol üòÖ In the Philippines, we have this thing called hugot which is what they‚Äôre both doing in this video. The guy initiated the hugot (flirty&fun teasing) which obviously caught her off guard but she was quick to return the hugot when she said can I go with you? (Context: He said can I give you a ticket so she jokingly responded with ‚ÄúYes, Can I go with you?‚Äù) We usually do hugot (flirty/romantic/sometimes cringe-worthy catchphrases) for fun. Y‚Äôall are misunderstanding her for something else when she‚Äôs obviously just having fun and enjoying life lmao You can tell that she‚Äôs friendly and competitive üòÇ Also, When we do hugot like this, it doesn‚Äôt necessarily mean that we are interested with the person. It‚Äôs one of our pastimes to have fun (it makes the other person cringe or feel silly but in a good way so you‚Äôre guaranteed to laugh/smile) I can‚Äôt count the number of times I was misunderstood by foreign people for this harmless fun lmao

text: I am a Caucasian American male married 51 years to my Chinese wife. Best wife in the world. I think even in my youth I was, at best, average-looking, but my lovely wife took to me fairly quickly and married me. But I was, in a way, one of those foreign guys. I was told a local guy had been in love for years with my future wife. Her parents moved her far away from him after her high school graduation. I actually felt sorry for him although I never met him. I can understand. But we must keep in mind he had years to get ready, he had no ambition, and my wife's parents correctly judged he was too immature. And whatever heartbreak he had, he continued to have the responsibility to find another girl who, if he exerted himself into some improvement, he could love and help. When we are young we have all these romantic notions, and romance is good, but we also must have the maturity after a while to search for answers, especially when we are young, having the years given us to take responsibility.

text: I lived near Manila for three years and observed some behaviors that left me frustrated. For example, I often saw people littering, urinating in public, and neglecting basic hygiene in their daily lives, such as unclean hands or kitchens. These experiences made me question whether these issues stem from a lack of education or other societal challenges.I also noticed some cultural habits that surprised me, such as women engaging in behaviors like spitting or not prioritizing personal grooming. Instead of addressing these, some seemed to simply cover up with makeup. Sadly, these impressions have left me unable to recommend the Philippines as a holiday destination.I found that preparing even simple meals or handling basic tasks like counting without a calculator seemed uncommon for some, and the increasing amount of garbage in the environment is concerning. Additionally, the frequent calls of "Hi Joe!" and interactions focused on money made me feel unwelcome at times, as though sincerity was lacking.I advise travelers to the Philippines to exercise caution and be mindful of potential scams. While there are certainly kind and genuine individuals, my overall experience was mixed, leaving me with some reservations about the country.

text: I think this is so sad to see this. I was a bad junkie and looked a lot like this myself. I shot up whatever I could, even stuff I really couldn't but tried to. I've shot everything from meth to heroin and dilaudid to morphine and never thought there was going to be a good end, only death was as good as it was going to get. I lost everything, my house, car, everything in my house, my friends and nearly everyone in my family. None of them wanted to sit around waiting for me to die but the worst thing I lost was myself, my self esteem, my self regard, and my mind and almost lost my will to live..I didn't want to live. Not like that, not hooked on drugs so bad I literally couldn't live without them..I couldn't live with them either. It was so hard to find help. I finally found it. I was doing drugs really my whole life but was addicted and shooting drugs for 7-8yrs. Oct. 5th 2020 I said goodbye to dope and I never looked back. I've never dipped my toe in the pond either, meaning I've never relapsed and I have no intentions of ever going back and could have so many times, I'm in constant, chronic pain 24/7/365 and I suck it up and deal with it and days like today is so very hard because the pain is so great. All I know is it could be worse, I could still be an addict right? I lost my legs due to drugs, my heart is done for, my liver was full of hep c with the worst genotype to fight which I had Nash also. I am dying now, but the difference now is I know it unlike my obliterated state when I not only didn't know, I didn't care either. Caring about it all now is the hardest way to live but I'm aware of everything. And it's so hard to get back on my feet it's damn near impossible. I can't work and I don't make enough to obtain housing. I live with the only family members who will take me in, 7 of us Ina small single wide trailer. My daughter and grandkids still hate me so I will never get them back and I only screwed up the one time and never put her or her kids in the midst of my hell. My two sons still care at least. Life is so hard but I'm alive, probably not for long but.im alive right now and maybe just maybe I will make it to another Xmas. I just want you addicts, even you nonaddicts, there's no sugar coating it life is going to be 50x harder than it was before your addiction. No one will ever treat you like they used to because you are nothing like you used to be. If anyone finds out you were an addict it will be no different as when you used to be an addict only your clean now, again that doesn't make one bit of difference. If they hated u before they hate you now. Especially health care workers. Don't ever make the mistake of telling them you USED TO BE AN ADDICT because you will be flagged and guaranteed you will be treated cruelly forever more. And plz, u health care workers don't tell me you aren't like that, YOUR ALL LIKE THAT. It's disgusting. Even society, you may get a handful compared to thousands that care but it's rare. However, don't take that as a reason to keep doing drugs, or to go back to drugs if you quit. No its not pretty out there, I thought it would be to and I was very disheartened when I found out how wrong I was but even so, if I could do it all over again I obviously wouldn't become an addict lol. Seriously tho, I won't ever go back to drugs. All those haters out there can just keep hating because it will not change my mind. I love the fact I'm clear headed and that I don't have that awful addiction on my back anymore controlling me. I control me now not the drugs or the dealers so stick with it and if you haven't quit yet do everything possible you can do to quit. If I ever do it again I am 100% sure it WILL kill me and for the first time in 52 yrs I actually want to live and I don't want to die but as sick as I am I wish my drs and nurses didn't hate me Iike they do. I might want to go to them instead of shortening my life staying away from them. Good luck and if anyone needs to talk to someone who walked in their shoes message me

text: Mental health issues isn't a joke. Don't film people in their worst. It can happen to you too or perhaps someone you love.Add: Getting clean doesn't just happen overnight, and fighting the withdrawal could take years. There needs to be ongoing support for patients who go through the process so they don't find themselves stuck again due to economic, financial, social, medical, etc. factors. One small hiccup and some are found using again. This is coming from a person who knew someone who had drinking issue due to her extreme depression brought on by a mental health disorder. Everyone chooses their own poison to numb the pain and in their worst, they can't tell right from wrong. On the flip side, there are people who start under peer pressure, which stems from their environment, company they lack or the company they have. It's a North American epidemic because the family system is compromised by many factors.

text: As a former iv drug addict that never dreamed it would be me that would fall hard and fast so damn easily, I feel like the desire to separate ourselves from this reality that causes us to recoil out of fear and disgust is what makes this disease so strong and hard to beat. We don't want to believe that it could happen to any one of us let alone the people we love and invest so much of ourselves in. I fear that this epidemic is fueled by the denial that so many of us cling to out of fear, anger, hatred, confusion and selfishness. And what makes it easy to deny and ignore is the selfishness of the disease. Addicts are survivors that can go to extreme lengths, taking from anyone to feed that cruel soulless monster that will eventually take over completely and cast out any remaining hints of the human that used to enhabit the body. If we truly want to rid the world of addiction we must not be afraid to really see it.
author: @nikkikidd8428

text: I'm an addict in recovery. I see nothing wrong with recording someone in this condition. You have no expectation of privacy in public. People need to see the reality of addiction. I thought I was fooling everyone and no one could tell I was high. Not one person had the nerve to say we see you, you're not fooling anyone. That enabled me. As far as not recording people in public, get high at home, if you don't have a home, get high where ever you sleep and stay there. You have no right no right to force others to endure the outcome of your addiction. It's selfish. And yes, that's a reminder to my own self. While the person this man is hurting the most is himself, he's also hurting the people who love him and society, look what him and and other addicts have done to that community. People leave, businesses leave. People who are stuck and can't leave suffer from the businesses leaving, the dangers that often come when there's abandoned buildings and so on. This is way deeper than videoing an addict on the street.

text: This is hard to stomach. I'm a firm believer that no addict chooses to be one. It's the lack of connection to other people, it's trauma. It's self medication when you feel lonely and helpless. The only comfort then is something to numb your aching soul. And at one point you're gone too far and you're not craving the connection anymore, it's replaced by whatever drug you used. The problem with this footage isn't that the person behind the camera isn't helping; it's that probably hundreds, thousands of people already walked past. It's the abandonment. It's the shame and neglect. This man is someone's son. Someone's brother, maybe a father to children himself. Imagine feeling so isolated and misunderstood that your last resort is something that makes you high.

text: I saw plenty of comments saying this video was abusive, I did some more research and found this:These pictures are of Misty Loman, a Kentucky woman who, while indeed suffering from appearance-altering bone cancer, was a drug addict and repeat drug offender, hence these mugshots. As of 2020 she was a year sober. She turned to drugs largely after losing three of her sons, as according to a source in her city of Bowling Green, WBKO. Both her drug use and bone cancer altered her appearance, but the untruth that it was only drugs responsible for it originated seemingly from a likely misinformed sheriff on social media. As stated earlier, she began recovery in late 2018 or early 2019 and was working with a faith-based recovery group.

text: What most people do not understand. Is Scolderma is 100% a fatal disease. 100% of the time as my grandmother had it. She was one of the oldest living survivors with it. She was written about in multiple medical texts and it really just depends on which part of the body that it attacks on. How long you live. Her's mostly attacked her skin and her esophagus and it was the methyltrexate that they gave her that ultimately killed her by taking out her liver. It's an incredibly painful disease as well because it literally turns either your organs or your skin because it's a connective tissue disease to rock. Which is why it's fatal if it turns your heart, your liver, or any of your internal organs to rock. Basically you can't survive that. Transplants are not usually allowable because it's something about the connective tissue, so it'll just redo it once you've done the transplant. They can't reverse that process of this point to my knowledge. To have both Lupus, Cancer and Scolderma is a horrible mix. I have lupus SLE SLE. I wouldn't wish that on anybody. What most people don't know also, is that if you are Rh negative, you have a much higher chance of having autoimmune illness. True facts and you have a much higher incidence of having a problematic pregnancies or miscarriage if you are Rh negative as well which nobody told me until after I'd had my own. Pays to know, there goes your rainbow, you're welcome.üòâ

text: Filipinos can have a little difficulty in pronouncing the R (not the long r), TH, F, V, and Z.In our native language we don't have F, V and Z. We only have P, B and S.While TH and R, on the other hand, seem a little bit funnier in our context. Everybody will laugh at you when you speak it in our own language and call you "yungit" (people who can't pronounce clearly). We only speak the long R like the Russians. Those yungit who can't pronounced S also might sound TH. Yungit, unfortunately, often get bullied.That's the reason (in my opinion, as a Filipino). But in my theory, there are two Filipino accent: the natural and the ideal. The Natural Filipino accent is the stereotypical accent (but 100% true). The Ideal Filipino accent is what you heard from educated Filipinos especially the teachers and college students.

text: My Mom is what we call a FilAm. She was born in the US (Stockton Ca in the late 1940s). My Dad is a true immigrant. Ennis County Clare Ireland. So, traditional medicine was always provided when we three kids were sick. My Irish Dad, when we kids got sick and he was in charge. text: Laugh so hard at this but related to this so much. As a child my dream was to be a veterinarian, but my mom and grandma wished for me to be a doctor especially my grandma because she believed I only wanted to be a vet so I wouldn‚Äôt have to talk to people (I was struggling with social anxiety and still am). When it came to college my Filipino family insisted on me being a nurse and to study medicine. I failed human anatomy 7 times but they called me ‚Äúlazy‚Äù and ‚Äúunfocused‚Äù. I ended up being force to study occupational therapy assistant and my grandma changed her dream for me to be a rehab director. I hated the profession and I didn‚Äôt understand it. The worse part was my anxiety was so bad I couldn‚Äôt do it and still wonder how I even passed and graduated with a degree in the field. I ended up going back to school and studying computer science and loved coding and the ‚Äúquiet‚Äù of not being near people, but I found my passion through the arts. My Filipino family were so shocked I decided to purse art rather than computer science. I didn‚Äôt care what they said and I was actually happy. I am now graduating with a degree in graphic design and I am interning for the hospital Kaiser as a graphic designer in their marketing department. Now instead of my family questioning my future and shitting on my dreams and passions it‚Äôs ‚Äúhow the hell did you get a job with them‚Äù to ‚Äúwe love your work‚Äù to ‚Äúyou should work here or there‚Äù. If I just followed what my family wanted I would be very unhappy and my anxieties would be a lot worse.

text: As a Filipino who grew up in the US because my dad served in the US Navy (God rest his soul), I would just like to add one other culture to this mix: Arabic. I did a DNA test on myself and found out that I am at least 1/3 Arabic, which totally shocked me. It didn't make sense at the time until I remembered that Arab traders had traveled to SE Asia, bringing Islam to Malaysia and Indonesia and eventually to the southern Philippine Islands. Though my family is from Central and Northern Luzon in the northern part of the country and predominantly Catholic, somehow a distant Arabic relative must have made his or her way through the region. Although my heritage showed no trace of an Arabic surname, it is filled with Spanish ones. The DNA test also showed I am predominantly Chinese and Indo-Chinese but hardly any Filipino/Malay blood. I feel like a mutt, go figure!

text: Bro, I'm Filipino-American, I find this funny. I am fucking dyin' rn man. ü§£üòÇI highly agree with the surname/last name bit, Filipinos do have Mexican/Latino sounding last names. For example, "Garcia" is one of the common-ass surnames in this world.I know one similarity that both Filipinos & Mexicans are very distant, lineal descendants from the Spanish.The language is similar too. Like when you want to ask "How are you?", People who speak Spanish go "¬øComo √©stas?" Filipinos can go one of three ways because there are many Filipino languages like Ilocano or Tagalog. It can be "Kamusta ka?", Kumusta po?", or "Kumusta na kayo?" It sounds similar. Even the food is similar. For example, you would've thought adobo came from the Philippines. But NO, it was originated by the Spanish. - It's also due to the fact that Filipinos, Mexicans, & the Spanish have authentic cooking. Especially the accent, Like from Fluffy (Gabriel Iglesias)'s joke about "How to tell Latinos Apart/Latinos are not all the Same." The way how someone speaks Spanish almost nearly works an almost similar way for Filipinos; a sometimes fast-paced, serious tone. And often loud. More on the accents, most Filipinos, mainly those who are native & are from the Motherland, The way they speak English is like "Aksahnt? I don't hab aksahnt. I sveak pfurfeckt englass." - Notice how sometimes the "F"'s are "P"s, and the "V"s are "B"s (Again, sometimes ;p ), I have no idea why, But I think it's sounds funny.Salamat, Gracias, Jo Koy.
